# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gtk-toolkit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] Cairo is used by GTK (versions 2.8 through 3.x), the Gecko layout engine in Mozilla Firefox, WebKit, Poppler, and Inkscape, among other projects.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] The library is dual-licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License version 2.1 and the Mozilla Public License 1.1.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] Keith Packard and Carl Worth created the project for use in the X Window System, originally naming it **Xr** (later **Xr/Xc**).
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] The name was changed in July 2003 to emphasize that the library was cross-platform and not tied to X11.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] Cairo 1.0 was released in 2005, providing a stable API.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] Version 1.2 (2006) added PDF and SVG backend support.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] Version 1.4 (2007) improved font handling and added the `cairo_push_group` API for offscreen rendering.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] Version 1.10 (2010) introduced the recording surface, which captures drawing operations for later replay, and the `cairo_region` API.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] In 2022, several legacy backends were removed, including BeOS, OS/2, DirectFB, and the OpenGL backend (which had been inactive for a decade).
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] GTK adopted Cairo for rendering in version 2.8 (2005), and GTK 3.0 (2011) used Cairo for all rendering.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] GTK 4 (2020) shifted to Vulkan and OpenGL renderers via GSK, reducing Cairo's role.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] A **source** provides color data, which may be a solid color, gradient, bitmap pattern, or another surface.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] The source is painted through the mask onto a **destination surface**, which represents the output backend.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] This approach differs from Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG), which attaches style attributes directly to shapes.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] Legacy backends for BeOS, OS/2, DirectFB, and OpenGL (direct and via glitz) were removed in 2022-2023.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] Experimental backends have been developed for OpenVG, Qt, Skia, and Direct2D.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] Bindings exist for C++, C# and other CLI languages, Delphi, Haskell, Julia, Lua, Perl, PHP, Python, Ruby, Rust, Scheme, and Smalltalk.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] Cairo handles Latin and CJK fonts but does not directly support complex text layout scripts that require glyph shaping.
[src:gtk-toolkit/cairo-graphics] The developers recommend using Pango for complex text, which integrates with Cairo for rendering.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The **GNU Image Manipulation Program**, commonly known by its acronym **GIMP** (/ɡɪmp/ ⓘ *GHIMP*; always stylized in capitals; formerly, **The GIMP**), is a free and open-source raster graphics editor.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] It is commonly used for photo retouching, image editing, free-hand drawing, and converting between different image file formats.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP is freely available on Microsoft Windows, Linux and macOS.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] It is licensed under the GNU General Public License (GPL 3.0 or later).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The project is a non-profit supported by a community of volunteers.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP supports plugins and scripting, allowing users to extend its features and automate tasks.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] While it is not primarily designed for drawing, some artists and creators still use it for that purpose.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] In 1995, Spencer Kimball and Peter Mattis began developing GIMP as a semester project at University of California, Berkeley for the eXperimental Computing Facility*.* The software was originally named the General Image Manipulation Program.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Kimball and Mattis formed the acronym GIMP by adding the letter G to "-IMP," inspired by a reference to "the gimp" in the 1994 film *Pulp Fiction*.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP's first public release, version 0.54, came out in 1996.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] It attracted many users, and a community of contributors grew around it.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] These contributors produced tutorials, shared artwork, and introduced improved workflows and techniques.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] During a visit to UC Berkeley in 1997, Richard Stallman of the GNU Project met with Kimball and Mattis where they asked him if they could change "General" in the program's name to "GNU".
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Stallman approved, and GIMP became part of the GNU software collection.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The initial release worked only on Unix-based systems such as Linux, SGI IRIX and HP-UX.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Since then, GIMP has been ported to other operating systems, including Microsoft Windows (1997, GIMP 1.1) and macOS.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] A GUI toolkit called GTK (at the time known as the GIMP ToolKit) was developed to facilitate the development of GIMP.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The development of the GIMP ToolKit has been attributed to Peter Mattis becoming disenchanted with the Motif toolkit GIMP originally used.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Wilber, the official mascot of GIMP, was created using GIMP by Tuomas Kuosmanen, known as *tigert*, on 25 September 1997.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Over time, other GIMP developers contributed additional accessories for Wilber, which are included in the *Wilber Construction Kit*.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The kit is available in GIMP's source code at `/docs/Wilber_Construction_Kit.xcf.gz`.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP is primarily developed by volunteers as a free and open source software project associated with both the GNU and GNOME projects.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Development takes place in a public git source code repository, on public mailing lists and in public chat channels on the GIMPNET IRC network.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] New features are held in public separate source code branches and merged into the main (or development) branch when the GIMP team is sure they won't damage existing functions.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Sometimes this means that features that appear complete do not get merged or take months or years before they become available in GIMP.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] After a source code release, installers and packages are made for different operating systems by parties who might not be in contact with the maintainers of GIMP.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The version number used in GIMP is expressed in a *major-minor-micro* format, with each number carrying a specific meaning: the first (major) number is incremented only for major developments (and is currently 3).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Previously, GIMP applied for several positions in the Google Summer of Code (GSoC).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] From 2006 to 2009 there have been nine GSoC projects that have been listed as successful, although not all successful projects have been merged into GIMP immediately.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Several of the GSoC projects were completed in 2008, but have been merged into a stable GIMP release later in 2009 to 2014 for Version 2.8.xx and 2.10.x.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Some of them needed some more code work for the master tree.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Second public Development 2.9-Version was 2.9.4 with many deep improvements after initial Public Version 2.9.2.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Third Public 2.9-Development version is Version 2.9.6.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] One of the new features is removing the 4 GB size limit of XCF file.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Increase of possible threads to 64 is also an important point for modern parallel execution in actual AMD Ryzen and Intel Xeon processors.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Version 2.9.8 included many bug fixes and improvements in gradients and clips.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Improvements in performance and optimization beyond bug hunting were the development targets for 2.10.0.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] MacOS Beta is available with Version 2.10.4.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The first release candidate for version 3.0, RC1, was released on 6 November 2024.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] After several more months of development, version 3.0 was completed and released on 16 March 2025.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] This represented the completion of seven years of development to complete a major overhaul of many of GIMP's features and dependencies.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP developers meet during the annual Libre Graphics Meeting.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Interaction designers from OpenUsability have also contributed to GIMP.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The current version of GIMP works with numerous operating systems, including Linux, macOS and Windows.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Many Linux distributions, such as Fedora Linux and Debian, include GIMP as a part of their desktop operating systems.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP began to host its own downloads after discontinuing use of SourceForge in 2013.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The website later repossessed GIMP's dormant account and hosted advertising-laden versions of GIMP for Windows.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] In 2022, GIMP was published on the Microsoft Store for Windows.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Tools used to perform image editing can be accessed via the toolbox, through menus and dialogue windows.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] They include filters and brushes, as well as transformation, selection, layer and masking tools.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP's developers have asserted that it has, or at least aspire to it having, similar functionality to Photoshop, but has a different user interface.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] There are several ways of selecting colors, including palettes, color choosers and using an eyedropper tool to select a color on the canvas.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The built-in color choosers include RGB/HSV/LAB/LCH selector or scales, water-color selector, CMYK selector and a color-wheel selector.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Colors can also be selected using hexadecimal color codes, as used in HTML color selection.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP has native support for indexed color and RGB color spaces; other color spaces are supported using decomposition, where each channel of the new color space becomes a black-and-white image.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] CMYK, LAB and HSV (hue, saturation, value) are supported this way.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Color blending can be achieved using the Blend tool, by applying a gradient to the surface of an image and using GIMP's color modes.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Gradients are also integrated into tools such as the brush tool, when the user paints this way the output color slowly changes.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] There are a number of default gradients included with GIMP; a user can also create custom gradients with tools provided.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP selection tools include a rectangular and circular selection tool, free select tool, and fuzzy select tool (also known as magic wand).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] More advanced selection tools include the select by color tool for selecting contiguous regions of color—and the scissors select tool, which creates selections semi-automatically between areas of highly contrasting colors.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP also supports a quick mask mode where a user can use a brush to paint the area of a selection.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Visibly this looks like a red colored overlay being added or removed.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The foreground select tool is an implementation of Simple interactive object extraction (SIOX), a method used to perform the extraction of foreground elements, such as a person or a tree in focus.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The Paths Tool allows a user to create vectors (also known as Bézier curves).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Users can use paths to create complex selections, including around natural curves.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] They can paint (or "stroke") the paths with brushes, patterns, or various line styles.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Users can name and save paths for reuse.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] There are many tools that can be used for editing images in GIMP.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The more common tools include a paint brush, pencil, airbrush, eraser and ink tools used to create new or blended pixels.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The Bucket Fill tool can be used to fill a selection with a color or pattern.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The Blend tool can be used to fill a selection with a color gradient.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] These color transitions can be applied to large regions or smaller custom path selections.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP also provides "smart" tools that use a more complex algorithm to do things that otherwise would be time-consuming or impossible.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] An image being edited in GIMP can consist of many layers in a stack.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The user manual suggests that "A good way to visualize a GIMP image is as a stack of transparencies," where in GIMP terminology, each level (analogous to a transparency) is called a layer.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Each layer in an image is made up of several channels.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] In an RGB image, there are normally 3 or 4 channels, each consisting of a red, green and blue channel.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Color sublayers look like slightly different gray images, but when put together they make a complete image.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The fourth channel that may be part of a layer is the alpha channel (or layer mask).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] This channel measures opacity where a whole or part of an image can be completely visible, partially visible or invisible.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Each layer has a layer mode that can be set to change the colors in the image.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Text layers can be created using the text tool, allowing a user to write on an image.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Text layers can be transformed in several ways, such as converting them to a path or selection.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Since GIMP 3.2, there are "link layers", which are linked duplicates to external source files.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Link layers automatically update changes that are made to the source files.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP has approximately 150 standard effects and filters, including Drop Shadow, Blur, Motion Blur and Noise.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP operations can be automated with scripting languages.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The Script-Fu is a Scheme-based language implemented using a TinyScheme interpreter built into GIMP.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP can also be scripted in Perl, Python (Python-Fu), or Tcl, using interpreters external to GIMP.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] New features can be added to GIMP not only by changing program code (GIMP core), but also by creating plug-ins.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] These are external programs that are executed and controlled by the main GIMP program.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] MathMap is an example of a plug-in written in C.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] There is support for several methods of sharpening and blurring images, including the blur and sharpen tool.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The unsharp mask tool is used to sharpen an image selectively – it sharpens only those areas of an image that are sufficiently detailed.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The Unsharp Mask tool is considered to give more targeted results for photographs than a normal sharpening filter.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The Selective Gaussian Blur tool works in a similar way, except it blurs areas of an image with little detail.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP-ML is an extension for machine learning with 15 filters.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The *Generic Graphics Library* (*GEGL*) was first introduced in GIMP 2.6 to improve how the software processes images.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Initially GIMP used GEGL for high bit-depth color operations, helping reduce data loss when adjusting colors.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP 2.8 was limited to 8-bit color, which is much lower than the 12-bit or higher depth that most digital cameras produce.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP 2.10 introduced full support for high bit-depth color, and hardware acceleration was enabled through OpenCL for some tasks.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP 3.0 introduces non-destructive filters, allowing users to apply effects without permanently changing the original image.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] This means they can be edited, toggled on or off, or removed after being applied.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Third-party filters are also supported, though they will not be retained if the necessary plugins are missing.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] CTX is a rasterizer for vector graphics introduced in GIMP 3.0.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] It allows certain simple shapes, such as lines and circles, to be converted into vector objects.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP supports importing and exporting with a large number of different file formats.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP's native format XCF is designed to store all information GIMP can contain about an image; XCF is named after the e*X*perimental *C*omputing *F*acility at UC Berkeley where GIMP was authored.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Import and export capability can be extended to additional file formats by means of plug-ins.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] XCF file size is extended to more than 4 GB since 2.9.6 and the new stable tree 2.10.x.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP's fitness for use in professional environments is regularly reviewed; it is often compared to and suggested as a possible replacement for Adobe Photoshop.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The single-window mode introduced in GIMP 2.8 was reviewed in 2012 by Ryan Paul of *Ars Technica*, who noted that it made the user experience feel "more streamlined and less cluttered".
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Michael Burns, writing for *Macworld* in 2014, described the single-window interface of GIMP 2.8.10 as a "big improvement".
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] Because of the free and open-source nature of GIMP, several forks, variants and derivatives of the computer program have been created to fit the needs of their creators.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] While GIMP is cross-platform, variants of GIMP may not be.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] These variants are neither hosted nor linked on the GIMP site.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] The GIMP site does not host GIMP builds for Windows or Unix-like operating systems either, although it does include a link to a Windows build.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gimp] GIMP's functionality can be extended with plugins.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] The name "GLib" originates from the project's start as a GTK C utility library.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] GLib implements functions that provide threads, thread programming and related facilities such as primitive variable access, mutexes, asynchronous queues, secure memory pools, message passing and logging, hook functions (callback registering) and timers.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] GLib also includes message passing facilities such as byte order conversion and I/O channels.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] The GLib package consisted of five libraries, but they were all merged into one library, since then named simply *GLib*, and are no longer sustained as standalone libraries.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] Of these, three continue to reside in distinct subdirectories of the source tree, and so can be thought of as discrete components: GLib, GObject, and GIO.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] These can be thought of as a software stack: GObject relies on GLib, and GIO provides higher-level functionality that uses both.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] GLib began as part of the GTK+ project, now named GTK.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] However, before releasing GTK+ version 2, the project's developers decided to separate code from GTK+ that was not for graphical user interfaces (GUIs), thus creating GLib as a separate software bundle.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] GLib was released as a separate library so other developers, those not using the GUI-related parts of GTK+, could use the non-GUI parts of the library without the overhead of depending on the full GUI library.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] Since GLib is a cross-platform library, applications using it to interface with the operating system are usually portable across different operating systems without major changes.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] For a current overview see https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/glib/-/blob/main/NEWS.
[src:gtk-toolkit/glib] The table below documents major patch notes from 1998 to 2025.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The **GLib Object System**, or **GObject**, is a free software library providing a portable object system and transparent cross-language interoperability.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] GObject is designed for use both directly in C programs to provide object-oriented C-based APIs and through bindings to other languages to provide transparent cross-language interoperability, e.g.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Depending only on GLib and libc, GObject is a cornerstone of GNOME and is used throughout GTK, Pango, ATK, and most higher-level GNOME libraries like GStreamer and applications.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Prior to GTK+ 2.0, code similar to GObject was part of the GTK codebase.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] At the release of GTK+ 2.0, the object system was extracted into a separate library due to its general utility.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] In the process, most non-GUI-specific parts of the `GtkObject` class were moved up into `GObject`, the new common baseclass.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Having existed as a separate library since March 11, 2002 (the release date of GTK+ 2.0), the GObject library is now used by many non-GUI programs such as command-line and server applications.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Though GObject has its own separate set of documentation and is usually compiled into its own shared library file, the source code for GObject resides in the GLib source tree and is distributed along with GLib.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] For this reason, GObject uses the GLib version numbers and is typically packaged together with GLib (for example, Debian puts GObject in its `libglib2.0` package family).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] At the most basic level of the GObject framework lies a generic and dynamic type system called GType.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The GType system holds a runtime description of all objects allowing glue code to facilitate multiple language bindings.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The type system can handle any singly inherited class structure, in addition to *non-classed* types such as opaque pointers, strings, and variously sized integers and floating point numbers.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The type system knows how to copy, assign, and destroy values belonging to any of the registered types.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] This is trivial for types like integers, but many complex objects are reference-counted, while some are complex but not reference-counted.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] When the type system "copies" a reference-counted object, it will typically just increase its reference count, whereas when copying a complex, non-reference-counted object (such as a string), it will typically create an actual copy by allocating memory.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] This basic functionality is used for implementing `GValue`, a type of generic container that can hold values of any type known by the type system.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Such containers are particularly useful when interacting with dynamically typed language environments in which all native values reside in such type-tagged containers.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Types that do not have any associated classes are called *non-classed*.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] These types, together with all types that correspond to some form of root class, are known as *fundamental types*: the types from which all other types are derived.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] These make up a relatively closed set, but although the average user is not expected to create their own fundamental types, the possibility does exist and has been exploited to create custom class hierarchies — i.e., class hierarchies not based on the `GObject` class.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Types that can be instantiated automatically by the type system are called *instantiable*.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] An important characteristic of these types is that the first bytes of any instance always contain a pointer to the *class structure* (a form of virtual table) associated to the type of the instance.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] For this reason, any instantiable type must be classed.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Contrapositively, any non-classed type (such as *integer* or *string*) must be non-instantiable.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] On the other hand, most classed types are instantiable, but some, such as interface types, are not.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] should be registered with the type system.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Some data structures that are too simple to be made full-fledged class types (with all the overhead incurred) may still need to be registered with the type system.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] to represent this structure, and provide functions for copying and freeing.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] GObject ships with a handful of boxed types wrapping simple GLib data types.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Another use for boxed types is as a way to wrap foreign objects in a tagged container that the type system can identify and will know how to copy and free.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Sometimes, for objects that need to be neither copied or reference-counted nor freed, even a boxed type would be overkill.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] ), it is often a good idea to create a derived pointer type, documenting the fact that the pointers should reference a particular kind of object, even though nothing else is said about it.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The GObject messaging system consists of two complementary parts: *closures* and *signals*.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Support exists for closures written in C and C++, as well as arbitrary languages (when bindings are provided).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] This allows code written in (for example) Python and Java to be invoked via a GObject closure.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Signals are the primary mechanism by which closures are invoked.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Objects register signal listeners with the type system, specifying a mapping between a given signal and a given closure.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Upon emission of a registered signal, that signal's closure is invoked.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] In GTK, all native GUI events (such as mouse motion and keyboard actions) can generate GObject signals for listeners to potentially act upon.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Each GObject class is implemented by at least two structures: the *class structure* and the *instance structure*.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] It must begin with the class structure of the superclass.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Class-specific variables can be used to emulate class members.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] (this ensures that all instances begin with a pointer to the class structure, since all fundamental instantiable types share this property).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] After the data belonging to the superclass, the structure can hold any instance-specific variables, corresponding to C++ member variables.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Defining a class in the GObject framework is complex, requiring large amounts of boilerplate code, such as manual definitions of type casting macros and obscure type registration incantations.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Also, since a C structure cannot have access modifiers like "public", "protected", or "private", workarounds must be used to provide encapsulation.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] One approach is to include a pointer to the private data — conventionally called `_priv` — in the instance structure.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The *private structure* can be declared in the public header file, but defined only in the implementation file, with the effect that the private data is opaque to users, but transparent to the implementor.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] If the private structure is registered with GType, it will be automatically allocated by the object system.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Indeed, it is not even necessary to include the `_priv` pointer, if one is willing to use the incantation `G_TYPE_INSTANCE_GET_PRIVATE` every time the private data is needed.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] To address some of these complexities, several higher-level languages exist that source-to-source compiles to GObject in C.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The Vala programming language uses a C#-style syntax and is pre-processed into vanilla C code.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The GObject Builder, or GOB2, offers a template syntax reminiscent of Java.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The combination of C and GObject is used in many successful free software projects, such as the GNOME desktop, the GTK toolkit and the GIMP image manipulation program.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Though many GObject applications are written entirely in C, the GObject system maps well into the native object systems of many other languages, like C++, Java, Ruby, Python, Common Lisp, and .NET/Mono.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] As a result, it is usually relatively painless to create language bindings for well-written libraries that use the GObject framework.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] For example, many Python programs use libraries written in C that use the GObject framework by using the PyGObject language binding.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] (A few of them are listed at Category:Software that uses PyGObject).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Writing GObject code in C in the first place, however, is relatively verbose.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The library takes a good deal of time to learn, and programmers with experience in high-level object-oriented languages often find it somewhat tedious to work with GObject in C.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] For example, creating a subclass (even just a subclass of `GObject`) can require writing and/or copying large amounts of boilerplate code.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] However, using Vala, a language that is designed primarily to work with GObject and which converts to C, is likely to make working with GObject or writing GObject based libraries nicer.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Although they are not really first-class objects (there are no actual metatypes in GType), metaobjects like classes and interfaces are created by GObject applications at runtime, and provide good support for introspection.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Since GObject provides a mostly complete object system for C, it can be seen as an alternative to C-derived languages such as C++ and Objective-C, though both also offer many other features beyond just their respective object systems.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] An easily observed difference between C++ and GObject is that GObject (like Java) does not support multiple inheritance.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] This tends to work against including GObject in software where resilience in the face of limited memory is important, or where very many or very large objects are commonly handled.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The g_try_new() can be used when a memory allocation is more likely to fail (for a large object for example), but this cannot grant that the allocation will not fail elsewhere in the code.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Another important difference is that while C++ and Objective-C are separate languages, GObject is strictly a library and as such does not introduce any new syntax or compiler intelligence.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] For example, when writing GObject-based C code, it is frequently necessary to perform explicit upcasting.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Hence, "C with GObject", also called "glib-flavored C", considered as a language separate from plain C, is a strict superset of plain C — like Objective C, but unlike C++.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] On platforms where there is no standard ABI that works across all C++ compilers (which is not usually the case, since either the Itanium ABI or the Microsoft ABI are usually followed), a library compiled with one C++ compiler is not always able to call a library compiled with a different one.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] If such compatibility is required, the C++ methods must be exported as plain C functions, partly defeating the purpose of the C++ object system.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] The problem occurs in part because different C++ compilers use different kinds of name mangling to ensure the uniqueness of all exported symbols.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Hence, despite being object-oriented, a GObject-based library written in C will always use the same external symbol names regardless of which compiler is used.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Perhaps the most profound difference is GObject's emphasis on signals (called events in other languages).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] This emphasis derives from the fact that GObject was specifically designed to meet the needs of a GUI toolkit.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Whilst there are signal libraries for most object-oriented languages out there, in the case of GObject it is built into the object system.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Because of this, a typical GObject application will tend to use signals to a much larger extent than a non-GObject application would, making GObject components much more encapsulated and reusable than the ones using plain C++ or Java.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] If using glibmm/gtkmm, the official C++ wrappers to Glib/GTK respectively, the sibling project libsigc++ allows easy use of underlying GObject signals using standard C++.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gobject] Of course, other implementations of signals are available on almost all platforms, although sometimes an extra library is needed, such as Boost.Signals2 for C++.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] The GTK team releases new versions on a regular basis.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK 4 and GTK 3 are actively maintained, while GTK 2 is no longer supported.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK 1 is independently maintained by the CinePaint project.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] The GTK library contains a set of graphical control elements (widgets); version 3.22.16 contains 186 active and 36 deprecated widgets.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK is an object-oriented widget toolkit written in the programming language C; it uses GObject (that is, the GLib object system) for object orientation.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] While GTK is mainly used with windowing systems based on Wayland (and prior to that on Wayland's predecessor X11), it works on other platforms, including Microsoft Windows (interfaced with the Windows API), and macOS (interfaced with Quartz).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] There is also an HTML5 back-end named *Broadway*, although this was deprecated in 2025 with the X11 backend to indicate both would be removed in GTK version 5.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK uses Vulkan or GL to draw most graphical elements.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK can be configured to change the look of the widgets drawn with its CSS engine.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] CSS can be used both at the system/user level, for all applications, and set by the application.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GDK acts as a wrapper around the low-level functions provided by the underlying windowing and graphics systems.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GSK is the rendering and scene graph API for GTK.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GSK lies between the graphical control elements (widgets) and the rendering.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GSK was finally merged into GTK version 3.90 released March 2017.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GtkBuilder allows user interfaces to be designed without writing code.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] The interface is described in an Extensible Markup Language (XML) file which is written by hand or generated by a GUI designer, which is then loaded at runtime and the objects created automatically.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] The description of the user interface is independent from the programming language being used.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Language bindings are available for using GTK from languages other than C, including C++, Genie, JavaScript, Perl, Python, Vala, and others.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK supports various backends, which provides different ways to display GTK applications depending on the system and environment.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] There are several GUI designers for GTK.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] The GTK Inspector is a built-in interactive debugging tool in GTK, allowing developers to inspect and modify UI elements, test CSS changes, and analyze widget structure in real time.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] It can be enabled using the `Control + Shift + I` or `Control + Shift + D` shortcuts, or by setting the `GTK_DEBUG=interactive` environment variable.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] It was introduced with GTK version 3.14.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK is mainly developed by The GNOME Project, which also develops the GNOME Development Platform and the GNOME Desktop Environment.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GNOME developers and users gather at an annual *GNOME Users And Developers European Conference* GUADEC meeting to discuss GNOME's current state and future direction.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GNOME incorporates standards and programs from freedesktop.org to better interoperate with other desktops.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Many GNOME applications have been ported to GTK 4, which was released in December 2020, however some still use GTK+ 3 (GIMP being a major one).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] The master branch of GTK utilizes Meson for its build automation.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK (and GNOME, GLib, etc.) formerly utilized the GNU Build System (named Autotools) as the build automation system of choice.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Since August 14, 2017, the Autotools build system files have been dropped.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] The most common criticism of GTK is the lack of backward-compatibility in major updates, most notably in the application programming interface (API) and theming.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] As a result, application and theme developers often have to rewrite parts of their code to ensure compatibility with newer version of GTK.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] The compatibility breaks between minor releases during the GTK 3.x development cycle was explained in 2013 by Benjamin Otte as due to strong pressures to innovate, such as providing the features modern users expect and supporting the increasingly influential Wayland display server protocol.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] With the release of GTK 4, the pressure from the need to innovate will have been released and the balance between stability and innovation will tip toward stability.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Similarly, recent changes to theming are specifically intended to improve and stabilise that part of the API, meaning some investment now should be rewarded later.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] However, in 2025, GTK 5 is described in the official documentation as "a major new version of GTK that breaks both API and ABI compared to GTK 4.x.", like GTK 3 and 4.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK programs can be run on desktop environments based on X11 and Wayland, or others including ones not made with GTK, provided the needed libraries are installed; this includes macOS if X11.app is installed.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK can be also run on Microsoft Windows.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] It is used by some popular cross-platform applications like Pidgin and GIMP. wxWidgets, a cross-platform GUI toolkit, uses GTK on Linux by default.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Other ports include DirectFB (for example used by the Debian installer).
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Several desktop environments utilize GTK as the widget toolkit.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] For syntax highlighting there is GtkSourceView, "source code editing widget".
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GtkSourceView is maintained by GNOME separately from GTK as a library: gtksourceview.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GtkSpell is a library separate from GTK.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Enchant is a wrapper for ispell, hunspell, etc., the actual spell checker engine/software.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GtkSpell uses GTK's GtkTextView widget, to highlight misspelled words and offer replacement.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Finally GTK was re-written to be object-oriented and was renamed GTK+.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] This was first used in the 0.99 release of GIMP.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK was subsequently adopted for maintenance by the GNOME Foundation, which uses it in the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] The GTK 2.0.0 release (2002) series introduced new features which include improved text rendering using Pango, a new theme engine, improved accessibility using the Accessibility Toolkit, transition to Unicode using UTF-8 strings, and a more flexible API.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Starting with version 2.8, released in 2005, GTK 2 depends on the Cairo graphics library for rendering vector graphics.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK version 3.0.0 (2011) included revised input device handling, support for themes written with CSS-like syntax, and the ability to receive information about other opened GTK applications.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] The '+' was dropped returning to simply 'GTK' in February 2019 during a Hackathon.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Release of the first GTK 4 version was in December 2020.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] At the 2018 edition of DevConf.cz, Matthias Clasen gave an overview of the then-current state of GTK 4 development, including a high-level explanation of how rendering and input worked in GTK 3, what changes were being made to GTK 4, and the reasons for those changes.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] Examples of things that have become possible with GTK 4 were given as well.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] One of the main changes made during the GTK 4 development cycle (i.e.
[src:gtk-toolkit/gtk] GTK 3.92, etc.) was the removal of user customization options (like individual keyboard shortcuts that could be set in GTK+ 2), and the delegation of functionality to ancillary objects instead of encoding it into the base classes provided by GTK.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] Full-function rendering of text and cross-platform support is achieved when Pango is used with platform APIs or third-party libraries, such as Uniscribe and FreeType, as text rendering backends.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] Pango-processed text will appear similar under different operating systems.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] Pango is a special-purpose library for text and not a general-purpose graphics rendering library such as Cairo, with which Pango can be used.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] The Cairo documentation recommends Pango be used to "render" text rather than Cairo for all but the simplest text "rendering".
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] The name pango comes from Greek *pan* (παν, 'all') and Japanese *go* (語, 'language').
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] In January 2000, the merger of the GScript and GnomeText projects was named Pango.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] Pango version 1.0.0 was released 11 March 2002.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] Pango 1.17 and newer support the 'locl' feature tag that allows localized glyphs to be used for the same Unicode code point.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] For an explanation of the substitutions rules for Romanian, see this discussion.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] Setting the locale via the POSIX environment variable, e.g.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] LANG=ro_RO.UTF-8 will also cause Pango to use 'locl' font feature.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] Since 1.37.1, Pango added more attributes to provide complete support for processing OpenType feature.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] Pango has been integrated into most Linux distributions.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] The GTK UI toolkit uses Pango for all of its text rendering.
[src:gtk-toolkit/pango] The Linux versions of the Mozilla Firefox web browser and Mozilla Thunderbird mail client use Pango for text rendering.
